(90, 3115, 'Suelos y secuestro de carbono', 'es', 'Soils and carbon sequestration', 'en', 'Soils and carbon sequestration', 23, 6, 2, '2013-09-03', NULL),
(91, 3115, 'En los últimos años, el suelo ha sido identificado como el mayor sumidero de carbono en el contexto de su ciclo global, adquiriendo especial importancia las actividades agrícolas debido a su extensión y a las numerosas opciones que presenta para fijar o emitir carbono. En estos sistemas, las emisiones de CO2 producidas por el empleo de maquinaria y por el manejo del suelo determinan los flujos que se establecen entre la vegetación, el suelo y la atmósfera, y por tanto la cantidad de carbono que puede ser almacenada.\r\n\r\nEn el suelo, reducir las emisiones de CO2 es sinónimo de aumentar la materia orgánica del suelo. En este sentido, en zonas agrícolas, los manejos deben ir encaminados a minimizar la alteración y erosión del suelo, aumentar el retorno de los residuos del cultivo y maximizar el uso eficiente de agua y nutrientes por el sistema. En este trabajo, la ausencia del laboreo en un cultivo de olivar ecológico dio lugar a un incremento en la concentración de carbono de 5,43 ± 1,28 Mg C ha-1 año-1, y a una tasa de fijación total de carbono por el suelo de 8,27 ± 1,57 Mg C ha-1 año-1 para el primer año con respecto a un olivar labrado.', 'es', 'In recent years, the ground has been identified as the largest carbon sink in the context of its global cycle, acquiring special importance agricultural activities due to its extension and the numerous options to fix or emit carbon. In these systems, the CO2 emissions produced by the use of machinery and by the management of soil determine flows established among vegetation, soil and atmosphere, and therefore the amount of carbon that can be stored.\r\n\r\nIn the soil, reduce CO2 emissions is synonymous with increasing the organic matter of the soil. In this sense, in agricultural areas, managements must be aimed to minimize disturbance and soil erosion, increase the return of crop residues and maximize the efficient use of water and nutrients by the system. In this work, the absence of tillage in organic olive cultivation resulted in an increase in the concentration of carbon of 5.43 ± 1.28 Mg C ha-1 year-1, and at a rate of total carbon fixation by soil of 8.27 ± 1.57 Mg C ha-1 year-1 for the first year with respect to an olive wrought.', 'en', 'In recent years, the ground has been identified as the largest carbon sink in the context of its global cycle, acquiring special importance agricultural activities due to its extension and the numerous options to fix or emit carbon. In these systems, the CO2 emissions produced by the use of machinery and by the management of soil determine flows established among vegetation, soil and atmosphere, and therefore the amount of carbon that can be stored.\r\n\r\nIn the soil, reduced CO2 emissions are synonymous with increase in the organic matter of the soil. In this sense, in agricultural areas, managements must be aimed to minimize disturbance and soil erosion, increase the return of crop residues and maximize the efficient use of water and nutrients by the system. In this work, the absence of tillage in organic olive cultivation resulted in an increase in the concentration of carbon of 5.43 ± 1.28 Mg C ha-1 year-1, and at a rate of total carbon fixation by soil of 8.27 ± 1.57 Mg C ha-1 year-1 for the first year with respect to an olive wrought.', 23, 8, 2, '2013-09-03', NULL),
