(125, 3122, 'La pérdida de valor de nuestro entorno rural es consecuencia de lo que Zorita (1995) llamaba\r\nlas cuatro falacias. La primera, la tecnocrática, que presuponía que la administración era capaz de\r\ndar respuestas a esta situación, cuando ni las Facultades ni las Escuelas imparten una doctrina acorde\r\ncon las características y problemas de nuestro medio natural. La segunda, la demográfica, que\r\nsacralizaba una línea de pensamiento en la cual el desarrollo económico de un país y la reducción\r\nde su población rural son aspectos indisociables: nadie parece percatarse –señalaba Zorita- que en\r\nmuchas regiones estemos ya por debajo del umbral mínimo de población realmente activa para el\r\nmantenimiento del medio natural. La tercera, la contable, convencida de que la renta generada por\r\nlos sistemas agrarios tradicionales es insuficiente para mantener un nivel de vida digno en el medio\r\nrural. Y, la última, la falacia ecológica, que entendía la acción humana enemiga permanente de la\r\nnaturaleza.\r\nAlgunas cosas han ido cambiando, pero sigue siendo fácil reconocer el habitual recurso a la\r\ncosmética medioambientalista que denunciaba Naredo (1993)en los discursos oficiales, porque el\r\nprincipal lastre es la incapacidad para pensar el futuro fuera del paradigma del crecimiento económico\r\npermanente (Harribey, 2004).\r\nLos cambios de uso del suelo son componentes básicos del Cambio Global. Más del 63% de\r\nla SAU del país quedó declarada Zona Desfavorecida por la PAC. Tras nuestro ingreso en la CEE, se\r\nincentivó al abandono agrario no competitivo, y tierras modeladas por el hombre durante siglos\r\nquedaron sin horizonte. En tal contexto se mueven hoy los retos de las ingenierías rurales, y debería\r\nhacerlo gran parte de la política de I+D. Foros, como el del Programa 21/CENUMAD, subrayan la urgente\r\nnecesidad de establecer vínculos entre los sistemas tradicionales de usos de la tierra y las aplicaciones\r\nde la ciencia y la tecnología. Pero esto requiere la construcción de nuevas aproximaciones\r\ncientíficas en las que se franqueen los muros que separan a muchas disciplinas, (Terradas, 1999).\r\nAl eco preocupante de las falacias de Zorita, e intentando traspasar las tentaciones cosméticas,\r\nel ponente desarrolla sus experiencias y aproximaciones científicas, durante más de 25 años, en el\r\nestudio de los pastos y sistemas agrosilvopastorales de Andalucía Oriental.', 'es', 'The loss of value of our rural environment is a consequence of what he called Zorita (1995)\r\nthe four fallacies. The first, the technocratic, which presupposed that the Administration was capable of\r\nresponding to this situation, when neither the powers nor the schools teach chord doctrine\r\nthe characteristics and problems of our natural environment. The second, the demographic that\r\nIt sacralizaba a line of thought in which the economic development of a country and the reduction\r\nof its rural population are inextricably linked aspects: no one seems to realize - Zorita - noted that in\r\nmany regions are already below the threshold of truly active population for the\r\nmaintenance of the natural environment. The third, the accountant, convinced of the income generated by\r\ntraditional farming systems is insufficient to maintain a decent standard of living in the Middle\r\nrural. And the last, the ecological fallacy, which it understood human action permanent enemy of the\r\nnature.\r\nSome things have changed, but is still easy to recognize the usual appeal to the\r\nenvironmentalist cosmetics that Naredo (1993) denounced in the official speeches, because the\r\nmain ballast is the inability to think about the future outside the paradigm of economic growth\r\nPermanent (Harribey, 2004).\r\nLand use changes are basic components of Global change. More than 63% of\r\nthe UAA in the country was declared area disadvantaged by the CAP. After our entry into the EEC, is\r\nIt encouraged non-competitive agricultural abandonment, and Lands shaped by man over the centuries\r\nthey were without horizon. In such a context the challenges of rural engineering move today, and it should\r\ndo so much of the policy of r &amp; d. forums, such as the program 21/CENUMAD, underline the urgent\r\nneed to establish links between traditional systems of the land uses and applications\r\nof science and technology. But this requires the construction of new approaches\r\nscientific that are crossing the walls that separate many disciplines, (Terradas, 1999).\r\nThe disturbing echo of the fallacies of Zorita, and trying to go beyond cosmetic temptations,\r\nthe rapporteur develops its experiences and scientific approaches, for more than 25 years, in the\r\nstudy of pastures and systems agrosilvopastorales of Eastern Andalusia.', 'en', 'The loss of value of our rural environment is a consequence of the four fallacies, according to Zorita (1995). The first, the technocratic, which presupposed that the Administration was capable of responding to this situation, when neither the powers nor the schools teach chord doctrine the characteristics and problems of our natural environment. The second, the demographic that is a line of thought in which the economic development of a country and the reduction of its rural population are inextricably linked aspects: no one seems to realize. Zorita noted that many regions are already below the threshold of truly active population for the maintenance of the natural environment. The third, the accountant, convinced of the income generated by traditional farming systems is insufficient to maintain a decent standard of living in the Middle rural. And the last, the ecological fallacy, which has understood the human actions as permanent enemy of the nature.\r\nSome things have changed, but is still easy to recognize the usual appeal to the environmentalist cosmetics that Naredo (1993) denounced in the official speeches, because the main ballast is the inability to think about the future outside the paradigm of economic growth Permanent (Harribey, 2004).\r\nLand use changes are basic components of Global change. More than 63% of the UAA in the country was declared disadvantaged area by the CAP. After our entry into the EEC, non-competitive agricultural abandonment is encouraged, and lands shaped by man over the centuries were without horizon. In such a context, the challenges of rural engineering move today, and it should do so much of the policy of R&amp;D forums, such as the 21/CENUMAD program, which underlines the urgent need to establish links between traditional systems of  land use and applications of science and technology. But this requires the construction of new scientific approaches that are crossing the walls that separate many disciplines, (Terradas, 1999).\r\nWith the disturbing echo of the fallacies of Zorita, and in an effort to go beyond cosmetic temptations, the rapporteur develops its experiences and scientific approaches, for more than 25 years, in the study of pastures and agroforestry systems of eastern Andalusia. ', 23, 8, 2, '2013-09-03', NULL),
