(143, 3127, 'Bases agroecológicas para la gestión de la fertilidad del suelo en el contexto mediterráneo: estudio de caso', 'es', 'Agroecological foundations for the management of the fertility of the soil in the Mediterranean context: case study', 'en', 'Agroecological foundations for the management of soil fertility in the Mediterranean context: case study', 23, 6, 2, '2013-09-03', NULL),
(144, 3127, 'En climas secos o semiáridos, los niveles de materia orgánica de los suelos de labranza son, a menudo, muy bajos. Por debajo de unos umbrales determinados, la pobreza de materia orgánica del suelo puede afectar a su funcionalidad y en ocasiones puede conducir a su degradación. En estas condiciones, el aumento de la reserva de materia orgánica puede redundar en mejoras importantes del funcionamiento del suelo más allá de la simple transferencia de nutrientes a los cultivos. La optimización de la funcionalidad de los suelos de labranza es uno de los principales objetivos de la gestión agroecológica. En suelos degradados, la recuperación de la funcionalidad tiene que ver con la reestructuración del suelo y, según parece, este proceso se daría más fácilmente en suelos libres de carbonatos. Los suelos de labranza con carbonatos son muy abundantes en la zona mediterránea y en climas secos y semiáridos, en general. La aplicación de fuentes de materia orgánica exógena constituye una técnica útil para la recuperación de la funcionalidad en suelos muy empobrecidos en materia orgánica. De todas maneras, la aplicación de fuentes de materia orgánica en el suelo puede tener efectos adversos, dependiendo de su calidad y de la dosis de aplicación. En este trabajo se estudian los cambios en la materia orgánica del suelo asociados al uso de enmiendas orgánicas en suelos mediterráneos carbonatados de clima seco y semiárido. Se observa que, tanto la dosis como la calidad de la materia orgánica utilizada, son importantes para la mejora de la calidad suelo.', 'es', 'In dry or semi-arid climates, levels of organic matter tillage soils are, often, very low. Below certain thresholds, the poverty of the soil organic matter can affect its functionality and can sometimes lead to its degradation. In these circumstances, the increase in organic matter reserve can cause significant improvements of the functioning of the soil further than the simple transfer of nutrients to crops. Optimizing the functionality of tillage soils is one of the main objectives of the ecological management. In degraded soils, recovery functionality has to do with the restructuring of the soil and, apparently, this process would be more readily in soils free of carbonates. Tillage with carbonate soils are very abundant in the Mediterranean and semi-arid, and dry climates in general. The application of exogenous organic matter sources is a useful technique for the recovery of functionality in very impoverished soils in organic matter. Anyway, the application of sources of organic matter in the soil can have adverse effects, depending on their quality and the application rate. In this paper we study changes in soil organic matter associated with the use of organic amendments in Mediterranean carbonated soils in dry and semi-arid climate. Shown that, both the dose and the quality of organic matter used, are important for the improvement of soil quality.', 'en', 'In dry or semi-arid climates, the levels of organic matter in tillaged soils are, often, very low. Below certain thresholds, the poverty of the soil organic matter can affect its functionality and can sometimes lead to its degradation. In these circumstances, the increase in organic matter reserve can lead to significant improvements of the functioning of the soil further than the simple transfer of nutrients to crops. Optimizing the functionality of soil tillage is one of the main objectives of the ecological management. In degraded soils, recovery functionality has to do with the restructuring of the soil and, apparently, this process would be more readily in soils free of carbonates. Tillage with carbonate soils is very abundant in the Mediterranean and semi-arid, and dry climates in general. The application of exogenous organic matter sources is a useful technique for the recovery of functionality in very impoverished soils in organic matter. Anyway, the application of sources of organic matter in the soil can have adverse effects, depending on their quality and the application rate. In this paper we study the changes in soil organic matter associated with the use of organic amendments in Mediterranean carbonated soils in dry and semi-arid climate. It is shown that, both the dose and the quality of organic matter used, are important for the improvement of soil quality.', 23, 8, 2, '2013-09-03', NULL),
