(155, 3129, 'Degradación de plaguicidas durante el proceso de compostaje de residuos agrarios', 'es', 'Degradation of pesticide during the process of composting of agricultural waste', 'en', 'Degradation of pesticide during the process of composting of agricultural waste', 23, 6, 2, '2013-09-03', NULL),
(156, 3129, 'El compostaje es uno de los procesos clave en producción ecológica, al transformar los residuos agroindustriales y ganaderos en productos con valor fertilizante y capacidad para mejorar las propiedades del suelo. Está demostrado que si el proceso se lleva a cabo correctamente, las temperaturas que se alcanzan son capaces de sanear el compost\r\neliminando los patógenos que pudieran contener los materiales de partida. Sin embargo, la presencia de residuos de fitosanitarios procedentes de tratamientos efectuados al material vegetal utilizado no había sido estudiada para las condiciones de Canarias, donde se realiza el compost con restos de empaquetado de plátano y restos de cultivo de tomate, estos materiales,\r\npor otra parte, pueden constituir un problema ambiental en determinadas situaciones de acumulación. Con el fin de comprobar si el compostaje degradaba los fitosanitarios aplicados, se llevó a cabo un ensayo consistente en la elaboración de dos pilas de compost a partir de\r\nestiércol de vaca, restos de poda y los restos vegetales indicados, tratados inmediatamente antes de la construcción de las pilas con tres productos fitosanitarios (clorpirifos, mancozeb y penconazol) a las dosis medias indicadas en la etiqueta. Se realizó un seguimiento de la temperatura de las pilas, a las que se aplicaron dos volteos en tres meses, muestreando\r\nperiódicamente el material para monitorizar los niveles de cada materia activa. Se comprueba que el compostaje disminuye la concentración de los fitosanitarios, sin llegar a disiparlos totalmente, aunque no se detectan residuos en el cultivo realizado posteriormente sobre sustrato con 25 % de este compost.', 'es', 'Composting is one of the key processes in organic production, to transform the agro-industrial and livestock waste into products with fertilizer value and capacity to improve the properties of the soil. It is shown that if the process is carried out correctly, the temperatures that are reached are able to clean up the compost\r\neliminating pathogens that might contain the starting materials. However, the presence of residues of plant protection treatments performed material from used vegetable had not been studied for the conditions of the Canary Islands, where takes place the compost with remains of packaging of banana and tomato crop remains, these materials,\r\non the other hand, may constitute an environmental problem in certain situations of accumulation. In order to check if the composting degrading the applied plant protection, carried out a test consisting of two batteries of compost making from\r\ncow dung, remains of pruning and the plant remains listed, treated immediately before the construction of batteries with three pesticides (Chlorpyrifos, mancozeb and penconazol) to medium doses listed on the label. The temperature of the batteries, which two volts were applied in three months, sampling is tracked\r\nperiodically the material to monitor levels of each active substance. Checks that composting reduces the concentration of the plant, to dispel them completely, although undetected residues in the crop made subsequently on substrate with 25% of this compost.', 'en', 'Composting is one of the key processes in organic production, to transform the agro-industrial and livestock waste into products with fertilizer value and capacity to improve the properties of the soil. It is shown that if the process is carried out correctly, the temperatures that are reached are able to clean up the compost eliminating pathogens that the starting materials might contain. However, the presence of residues of plant protection treatments performed on material from used vegetables had not been studied for the conditions of the Canary Islands, where the composting with remains of packaging of banana and tomato crop remains takes place. These materials, on the other hand, may constitute an environmental problem in certain accumulation situations. In order to check if the degradation is applied to plant protection material through composting, a test was carried out consisting of two batteries of compost making from cow dung, remains of pruning and the plant remains listed, treated immediately before the construction of batteries with three pesticides (Chlorpyrifos, mancozeb and penconazol) to medium doses listed on the label. The temperature of the batteries, which two volts were applied in three months, was tracked periodically in the material to monitor levels of each active substance. Checks that composting reduces the concentration of the plant, to dispel them completely, although undetected residues in the crop made subsequently on substrate with 25% of this compost.', 23, 8, 2, '2013-09-03', NULL),
