(177, 3133, 'Erosión hídrica en campos de agricultura extensiva de secano. Campo experimental de la finca la higueruela (Toledo)', 'es', 'Water erosion in areas of extensive rainfed agriculture. Experimental field of the estate the higueruela (Toledo)', 'en', 'Water erosion in areas of extensive rainfed agriculture. Experimental field of the estate the Higueruela (Toledo)', 23, 6, 2, '2013-09-03', NULL),
(178, 3133, 'Se presenta el campo experimental sobre erosión de suelos agrícolas de la finca La Higueruela (CSIC, Toledo) y la instrumentación de campo desarrollada para la monitorización de procesos hidrológicos y erosivos. El campo experimental cuenta con 28 parcelas de erosión tipo USLE, en las\r\nque se reproducen los principales usos y manejos agrícolas representativos de la agricultura de secano mediterránea, incluyendo cultivos de cereal y barbechos con prácticas de no laboreo, mínimo\r\nlaboreo y laboreo convencional. El campo experimental funciona desde 1992, por lo que se dispone de una serie de datos de 18 campañas agrícolas (1993/94 a 2010/11), hecho destacable dada la escasa\r\ninformación de campo disponible en cuanto a tasas de erosión en este tipo de paisajes agrícolas y la importancia de la conservación de suelo en estos paisajes. \r\n\r\nLos resultados muestran que las parcelas experimentales de erosión son una herramienta útil para evaluar y comparar las respuestas hidrológicas y erosivas de diferentes modelos de manejo agrícola, así como para analizar los factores que intervienen en dichas respuestas. Por otro lado,\r\nlos resultados confirman la gran variabilidad de las precipitaciones y de su erosividad en el clima Mediterráneo; y revelan diferencias en las respuestas hidrológicas y erosivas en los diferentes manejos. Esta variabilidad pone de manifiesto la importancia de disponer de largas series temporales de datos de campo sobre los distintos manejos del suelo para validar y calibrar modelos predictivos de erosión, así como para elaborar los modelos de gestión del territorio que consideren como premisa la sostenibilidad del suelo.', 'es', 'Presents the experimental field on erosion of agricultural soils from the farm La Higueruela (CSIC, Toledo) and field instrumentation developed for the monitoring of hydrological and erosion processes. The experimental field has 28 plots of erosion type USLE, in the\r\nplaying the main uses and agricultural management of rainfed agriculture Mediterranean, including cereal crops and fallow practices of non-tillage, minimum\r\ntillage and conventional tillage. The experimental field work since 1992, so it is available a series of data of 18 agricultural campaigns (1993/94 to 2010/11), remarkable fact given the scarce\r\nfield information available in regards it rates of erosion in this type of agricultural landscapes and the importance of the conservation of soil in these landscapes. \r\n\r\nThe results show that the erosion plots are a useful tool to assess and compare the hydrologic and erosive responses of different agricultural management models, as well as to analyze the factors involved in such responses. On the other hand\r\nthe results confirm the high variability of rainfall and its erosion in the Mediterranean climate; and they reveal differences in hydrologic and erosive responses in the different management. This variability reveals the importance of long time series of data on the different soil management to validate and calibrate predictive models of erosion, as well as to develop models of land management deemed as a premise the sustainability of the soil.', 'en', 'Presents the experimental field on erosion of agricultural soils from the farm La Higueruela (CSIC, Toledo) and the field instrumentation developed for the monitoring of hydrological and erosion processes. The experimental field has 28 plots of erosion type USLE, in the playing the main uses and agricultural management of rainfed agriculture Mediterranean, including cereal crops and fallow practices of non-tillage, minimum tillage and conventional tillage. The experimental field work since 1992, so it is available a series of data of 18 agricultural campaigns (1993/94 to 2010/11), remarkable fact given the scarce field information available regarding the rates of erosion in this type of agricultural landscapes and the importance of the conservation of soil in these landscapes. \r\n\r\nThe results show that the erosion plots are a useful tool to assess and compare the hydrologic and erosive responses of different agricultural management models, as well as to analyze the factors involved in such responses. On the other hand the results confirm the high variability of rainfall and its erosion in the Mediterranean climate; and they reveal differences in hydrologic and erosive responses in the different management. This variability reveals the importance of long time series of data on the different soil management to validate and calibrate predictive models of erosion, as well as to develop models of land management deemed as a premise the sustainability of the soil.', 23, 8, 2, '2013-09-03', NULL),
