(183, 3134, 'Pérdidas de agua por escorrentía superficial en campos agrícolas de secano Mediterráneo', 'es', 'Loss of water by surface runoff in Mediterranean rainfed farmland', 'en', 'Loss of water by surface runoff in Mediterranean rainfed farmland', 23, 6, 2, '2013-09-03', NULL),
(184, 3134, 'Se estudian las pérdidas de agua por escorrentía superficial en campos agrícolas de secano mediterráneo atendiendo a dos factores: los coeficientes medios anuales de escorrentía y su variabilidad estacional. Se presentan los resultados relativos a precipitaciones y coeficientes de escorrentía obtenidos en parcelas experimentales tipo USLE durante 17 campañas agrícolas consecutivas (1993/94 a 2009/10), situadas en el campo experimental sobre erosión de suelos agrícolas de la finca La Higueruela (CSIC, Toledo), incluyendo cultivos de cebada y barbechos con prácticas de laboreo convencional y mínimo laboreo.\r\n\r\nLos resultados muestran que las pérdidas totales de agua por escorrentía son muy reducidas para toda la serie analizada, siendo el coeficiente anual medio inferior al 5% de la precipitación total. Además, se relacionan las mayores producciones de escorrentía con dos tipos de situaciones\r\nmeteorológicas: eventos aislados de elevada intensidad de lluvia, característicos de los meses de verano, y situaciones de temporal en las que el suelo alcanza la saturación, generalmente durante los meses de invierno. Situaciones, en las que la capacidad de infiltración del suelo se ve superada por un aporte excesivo de agua o por la saturación previa del mismo, con independencia del manejo agrícola aplicado en el suelo. Al mismo tiempo, los resultados revelan la necesidad de disponer de\r\nlargas series temporales de datos de campo para poder evaluar la pérdida de agua por escorrentía superficial que tiene lugar en los campos agrícolas y la importancia de validar las distintas prácticas de conservación orientadas a reducir dicha pérdida de agua.', 'es', 'Water losses are studied by surface runoff in Mediterranean rainfed agricultural fields according to two factors: annual average coefficients of runoff and its seasonal variability. Presents the results related to precipitation and runoff coefficients obtained in experimental plots type USLE during 17 agricultural consecutive campaigns (1993/94 to 2009/10), located in the experimental field on erosion of agricultural soils of the finca La Higueruela (CSIC, Toledo), including barley crops and fallow land with conventional tillage and minimum tillage practices.\r\n\r\nThe results show that the total loss of water by runoff are very small for the entire series analyzed, being the annual ratio between less than 5% of the total precipitation. In addition, the largest production runoff relate to two types of situations\r\nWeather: isolated high-intensity rain events, typical of the summer months, and temporary situations in which the soil reaches saturation, usually during the winter months. Situations, in which the soil infiltration capacity is surmounted by an excessive water intake or prior saturation of it, regardless of the agricultural management applied in soil. At the same time, the results show the need of\r\nlong time series of field data to assess the loss of water by surface runoff which takes place in the agricultural fields and the importance of validating the various conservation practices aimed to reduce the loss of water.', 'en', 'Water losses by surface runoff are studied in Mediterranean rainfed agricultural fields according to two factors: annual average coefficients of runoff and its seasonal variability. This paper presents the results related to precipitation and runoff coefficients obtained in experimental plots type USLE during 17 agricultural consecutive campaigns (1993/94 to 2009/10), located in the experimental field on erosion of agricultural soils of the finca La Higueruela (CSIC, Toledo), including barley crops and fallow land with conventional tillage and minimum tillage practices.\r\n\r\nThe results show that the total loss of water by runoff are very small for the entire series analyzed, being the annual ratio between less than 5% of the total precipitation. In addition, the largest production runoff relate to two types of situations\r\nWeather: isolated high-intensity rain events, typical of the summer months, and temporary situations in which the soil reaches saturation, usually during the winter months. Situations in which the soil infiltration capacity is surmounted by an excessive water intake or prior saturation of it, regardless of the agricultural management applied in soil. At the same time, the results show the need of long time series of field data to assess the loss of water by surface runoff which takes place in the agricultural fields and the importance of validating the various conservation practices aimed to reduce the loss of water.', 23, 8, 2, '2013-09-03', NULL),
