(189, 3135, 'El manejo del suelo y del paisaje en las campiñas Andaluzas', 'es', 'Management of soil and landscape in the Andalusian countryside', 'en', 'Management of soil and landscape in the Andalusian countryside', 23, 6, 2, '2013-09-03', NULL),
(190, 3135, 'Los efectos de las lluvias de último año (arrastre del suelo e inundaciones) han hecho visible para un sector de la sociedad lo que en las últimas décadas veníamos denunciando desde el ámbito de la agroecología: que la erosión del suelo es el problema ambiental más grave para la sostenibilidad de la agricultura andaluza. La principal causa de este desastre ecológico es el desequilibrio provocado por un modelo de agricultura intensiva basada en el laboreo y/o uso de herbicidas que deja\r\nel suelo desnudo y favorece los procesos de erosión y desertificación. El enorme coste económico, social y ambiental que supone la pérdida del suelo agrícola, sin embargo, no es percibido como un problema por nuestra sociedad. En esta comunicación desglosamos un conjunto de actuaciones de fácil y económica implementación por el agricultor, que deben ser fomentadas/financiadas/controladas por las administraciones públicas, como: rediseñar adecuadamente las parcelas de las fincas y recuperar la vegetación autóctona original en linderos y márgenes de cauces y caminos, establecer manchones de vegetación arbórea/arbustiva autóctona en las zonas más marginales, reducir al máximo el laboreo y el uso de herbicidas y fomentar las técnicas de agricultura de conservación, con el uso obligatorio de cubiertas vegetales en plantaciones arbóreas y en el barbecho de cultivos anuales, fomentar y apoyar la asociación de ganadería extensiva con sistemas agroforestales, entre otras. Estas actuaciones, manejadas globalmente, además de ayudar en la lucha contra la pérdida de suelo y de biodiversidad, contribuirán a mejorar un paisaje agrícola actualmente enormemente deteriorado.', 'es', 'The effects of the rains of last year (drag from the ground and floods) have made visible to a sector of society that in recent decades had been reported from the field of Agroecology: that soil erosion is the most serious environmental problem for the sustainability of the Andalusian agriculture. The main cause of this ecological disaster is the imbalance caused by a model of intensive agriculture based on tillage and/or use of herbicides leaves\r\nthe ground bare and favors processes of erosion and desertification. The enormous economic, social and environmental cost that implies the loss of agricultural land, however, is not perceived as a problem for our society. In this communication break down a set of performances of easy and economical implementation by the farmer, which should be encouraged/supported/controlled by public administrations, as: properly redesign the plots of farms and recover the original native vegetation in boundaries and margins of runways and roads, set up patches of native tree/shrub vegetation in more marginal areas, to minimize tillage and the use of herbicides and promote conservation agriculture techniqueswith the obligatory use of Mulches, tree plantations and annual crops fallow, encouraging and supporting the Association of ranching with agroforestry systems, among others. These performances, handled globally, as well as helping in the fight against the loss of land and biodiversity, will help improve a currently greatly impaired agricultural landscape.', 'en', 'The effects of the rains of last year (drag from the ground and floods) have made visible to a sector of society that in recent decades had been reported from the field of Agroecology: that soil erosion is the most serious environmental problem for the sustainability of the Andalusian agriculture. The main cause of this ecological disaster is the imbalance caused by a model of intensive agriculture based on tillage and/or use of herbicides which leaves the ground bare and favours processes of erosion and desertification. The enormous economic, social and environmental cost that implies the loss of agricultural land, however, is not perceived as a problem for our society. In this communication break down a set of performances of easy and economical implementation by the farmer, which should be encouraged/supported/controlled by public administrations, as: properly redesign the plots of farms and recover the original native vegetation in boundaries and margins of runways and roads, set up patches of native tree/shrub vegetation in more marginal areas, to minimize tillage and the use of herbicides and promote conservation agriculture techniques with the obligatory use of Mulches, tree plantations and annual crops fallow,encouraging and supporting the Association of ranching with agroforestry systems, among others. These performances, handled globally, as well as helping in the fight against the loss of land and biodiversity, will help improve a currently greatly impaired agricultural landscape.', 23, 8, 2, '2013-09-03', NULL),
