(488, 3677, 'Produire des agrumes en agriculture biologique', 'fr', 'Produce citrus organically', 'en', 'Produce oranic citrus ', 89, 6, 2, '2013-11-08', NULL),
(489, 3677, 'Les agrumes occupent la première place des productions fruitières dans le monde avec 96 millions de tonnes produites en 2000 (Source FAO, 2001). Leur culture s’étend des zones tempérées chaudes aux zones tropicales entre 40° de latitude Nord et de latitude Sud, la région Corse correspondant à la limite nord de leur culture. La clémentine et le pomelos sont les deux cultures majoritaires. La clémentine de Corse cueillie à maturité avec la présence de feuilles a récemment fait l’objet d’une certification IGP (Indice Géographique Protégé). La production corse biologique et conventionnelle, toutes espèces confondues, est de l’ordre de 26 000 tonnes dont plus de 20 000 de clémentines (Données Agreste 2003). En France, les surfaces consacrées aux agrumes biologiques atteignent 2% des surfaces fruitières biologiques totales. La Corse compte 135 ha d’agrumes biologiques pour 18 producteurs. Cette fiche technique aborde l''implantation du verger, le matériel végétal (les porte-greffes, les espèces et variétés d''agrumes cultivées), la conduite du verger d''agrumes (fertilisation, taille, itinéraire technique, récolte), la protection phytosanitaire (ravageurs : cochenille chinoise, pou rouge de Californie, cochenilles virgules et serpette, cochenille australienne, cochenille farineuse, cochenille noire de l''olivier, cochenille plate, mineuse des agrumes, mouche méditerranéenne des fruits, cicadelle pruineuse ; maladies : gommose, maladie de conservation).', 'fr', 'Citrus occupy first place in fruit production in the world with 96 million tonnes produced in 2000 (Source FAO, 2001). Their culture extends warm temperate to tropical areas between 40 ° North latitude and latitude South, the island of Corsica at the northern limit of their culture. The clementine and the pomelos are both majority cultures. The Clémentine de Corse picked at maturity with the presence of leaves has recently been a PGI (protected geographical index) certification. The Corsican organic and conventional production, all species, is about 26 000 tonnes of which more than 20,000 of clementines (Agreste 2003 data). In France, the surfaces dedicated to organic citrus reach 2% of the total organic fruit area. Corsica has 135 ha of organic citrus for 18 producers. This fact sheet discusses the establishment of the orchard, the plant material (rootstocks, the species and varieties of citrus fruits), the conduct of the citrus Orchard (fertilization, size, technical route, harvesting), plant protection (pests: Chinese cochineal, California red scale, commas and serpette, Australian cochineal scale insects, floury cochineal, olive black cochineal, cochineal flat, citrus Leafminer, Mediterranean fruit fly, pruinose leafhopper; diseases) (: gummosis, conservation).', 'en', 'Citrus occupy first place in fruit production in the world with 96 million tonnes produced in 2000 (Source FAO, 2001). Their culture extends warm temperate to tropical areas between 40 ° North latitude and latitude South, the island of Corsica at the northern limit of their culture. The clementine and the pomelos are both majority cultures. The Clémentine de Corse picked at maturity with the presence of leaves has recently been a PGI (protected geographical index) certification. The Corsican organic and conventional production, all species, is about 26 000 tonnes of which more than 20,000 of clementines (Agreste 2003 data). In France, the surfaces dedicated to organic citrus reach 2% of the total organic fruit area. Corsica has 135 ha of organic citrus for 18 producers. This fact sheet discusses the establishment of the orchard, the plant material (rootstocks, the species and varieties of citrus fruits), the conduct of the citrus Orchard (fertilization, size, technical route, harvesting), plant protection (pests: Chinese cochineal, California red scale, commas and serpette, Australian cochineal scale insects, floury cochineal, olive black cochineal, cochineal flat, citrus Leafminer, Mediterranean fruit fly, pruinose leafhopper; diseases) (: gummosis, conservation).', 89, 8, 2, '2013-11-08', NULL),
