(588, 3245, 'Los hongos micorrícicos como bioindicadores del tipo de manejo agrícola en suelos de viña', 'es', 'The mycorrhizal fungi as bio-indicators of the type of agricultural management in vineyard soils', 'en', 'The mycorrhizal fungi as bio-indicators of the type of agricultural management in vineyard soils', 23, 6, 2, '2013-11-13', NULL),
(589, 3245, 'Tradicionalmente, la fertilidad de los suelos agrícolas se ha contemplado desde una perspectiva estrictamente físico-química. Una visión agroecológica obliga a considerar el suelo como un sistema vivo, y a las interacciones entre las plantas y las comunidades microbianas del suelo, la base de la fertilidad y la salud de los agrosistemas. Los hongos formadores de las micorrizas arbusculares (MA) viven en el interior de la raíz de la mayor parte de las plantas con interés agronómico, y desde su posición de  privilegio modulan las interacciones rizosféricas del sistema de los habitantes de la zona fértil del suelo.\r\nPara determinar el efecto del tipo de manejo del cultivo sobre la salud de los suelos de viña en la isla de Tenerife, empleando como bioindicador la presencia de hongos MA, se seleccionaron y muestrearon una serie de fincas con diferente tipos de manejo del cultivo (convencional, ecológico\r\no en reconversión), en los municipios de Vilaflor y Buenavista. Los suelos recolectados fueron estudiados desde el punto de vista físico - químico y microbiológico, evaluando las poblaciones de hongos MA presentes.\r\nLos resultados demuestran que las fincas con manejo convencional presentan contenidos en fósforo (ppm, Olsen) estadísticamente superiores al resto de los suelos muestreados, y un menor contenido microbiano con respecto a los ecológicos, con valores medios de colonización radical hasta 4 veces superiores. A su vez, los suelos de fincas en reconversión tienen cinco veces menos cantidad de propágulos de hongos MA y la mitad de esporas en relación a las fincas tradicionalmente ecológicas.', 'es', 'Traditionally, the fertility of agricultural soils has contemplated a strictly physical-chemical perspective. An ecological vision forces to consider the soil as a living system, and the interactions between plants and microbial communities in soil, based on fertility and health of agrosystems. Fungi forming arbuscular mycorrhizas (MA) living inside the root of most of the plants with agronomic interest, and from its privileged position modulate interactions colonizing of the inhabitants of the fertile area of the ground system.\r\nTo determine the effect of the type of crop management on the health of soils in vineyard on the island of Tenerife, using as a biomarker for the presence of fungi MA, were selected and sampled a series of farms with different types (conventional, ecological crop management\r\nor in conversion), in the municipalities of Vilaflor and Buenavista. Harvested soils were studied from the point of view physical - chemical and microbiological, evaluating the populations of fungi present MA.\r\nThe results demonstrate that farms with conventional management are contained in phosphorus (ppm, Olsen) statistically superior to the rest of the sampled soils, and a lower microbial content with respect to the ecological, with average values of radical colonization up to 4 times higher. At the same time, farms in conversion soils have five times fewer propagules of fungi MA and half of spores in relation to traditionally ecological farms.', 'en', 'Traditionally, the fertility of agricultural soils has contemplated a strictly physical-chemical perspective. An ecological vision forces to consider the soil as a living system, and the interactions between plants and microbial communities in soil, based on fertility and health of agrosystems. Fungi forming arbuscular mycorrhizas (MA) living inside the root of most of the plants with agronomic interest, and from its privileged position modulate interactions colonizing of the inhabitants of the fertile area of the ground system.\r\nTo determine the effect of the type of crop management on the health of soils in vineyards on the island of Tenerife, using as a biomarker for the presence of fungi MA, a series of farms with different types (conventional, ecological crop management or in conversion), in the municipalities of Vilaflor and Buenavista were selected and sampled. Harvested soils were studied from the point of view physical - chemical and microbiological, evaluating the populations of fungi present MA.\r\nThe results demonstrate that farms with conventional management are contained in phosphorus (ppm, Olsen) statistically superior to the rest of the sampled soils, and a lower microbial content with respect to the ecological, with average values of radical colonization up to 4 times higher. At the same time, farms in conversion soils have five times fewer propagules of fungi MA and half of spores in relation to traditionally ecological farms.', 23, 8, 2, '2013-11-13', NULL),
